Files in the vrpn packages and souce directory:

VRPN (The Virtual Reality Peripheral Network) has been placed into the
public domain by the copyright owner Russell M. Taylor II at the University
of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.  Additional terms and requests follow:

1. Please acknowledge this library in any publication, written, videotaped,
	or otherwise produced, that results from making programs using it.
	The acknowledgement will credit

	GRIP Project
	Department of Computer Science,
	University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill,
	Supported by the NIH National Centers for Research Resources.

2. Please furnish us a copy of any publication, including videotape,
	that you produce and disseminate outside your group using our
	program.  These should be addressed to Professor R.M. Taylor.

3. The program and associated files are provided "as is," with no
	express or implied warranty.  You agree to hold the University
	of North Carolina and its employees and students, as well as
	all involved in the development of the system, not liable in
	the event of damages resulting from the use of this product.

4. You understand that the University cannot provide support for this
	product.  While we may release future, updated versions of the
	software and fix reported bugs, we may be unable to do so.
	Such releases and updates are likely to be reported on the
	project web page at http://www.cs.unc.edu/Research/vrpn.

5. Please send us derived classes and drivers for new devices that you
	create for the library.  We will attempt to include them in
	future releases of the library for you and others to use.  This
	is the fastest way to get a working system for everyone.

--

Files in quat packages and source directory:
This directory contains the source and test files for the quaternion
library, libquat.a.  It is based on Warren Robinett's adapted version of Ken
Shoemake's code, as seen in Shoemake's 1985 SIGGRAPH paper.

This code is has been placed into the public domain by the University of
North Carolina at Chapel Hill on January 9th, 2005; after consultation
with its authors, Warren Robinett and Richard Holloway.  It is provided
"as is", with no guarantee or warranty of any kind, even fitness for a
specific purpose.

--

